\begin_layout Subsection
Calculating Photometry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a fits file and the celestial coordinates of a celestial object (star,
 galaxy or anything that emits enough light) that is seen in the fits file
 image, calculating this object's photometry is rather simple.
 The fits file gives the information of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

counts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of each pixel in the image, so to calculate the object's brightness one
 needs to choose an aperture (preferably as close to the object as possible)
 and sum the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

counts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the pixels that are within the aperture.
 In practice we had to deal with some complexity that will be decribed in
 the next few sections, as well as our solutions to these problems.
 The measured flux of an object, in the native units of the fits image file,
 will be denoted as DN.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Aperture Photometry package for python
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of the calculating work is done by the Photutils package
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Aperture Photometry in Photutils"
target "https://photutils.readthedocs.io/en/stable/aperture.html"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 that is designed to calculate photometry, when given a fits file, celestial
 coordinates and an aperture radius.
 The package calculate an object's DN in data units and give a more accurate
 result than simply summing up pixel values.
 This is becuase when summing up pixels we don't sum up light within a circle,
 
\color black
so a more complcated calculation is requierd here
\color inherit
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Units"

\end_inset

Units
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The value, or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

counts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, of each pixel varies between surveys.
 We want to find the photometry values in magnitudes, so for each survey
 we use a different convertion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
SDSS - an SDSS fits file counts are in nanomaggy (nMgy) units.
 A "maggy" is the flux density 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\nu}$
\end_inset

 of the (singel pixel) 
\color black
source relative
\color inherit
 to the standard source 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{0}$
\end_inset

 (which defines the zeropoint of the magnitude scale).
 The convertion from nMgy to AB magnitudes is the following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sdss-nmgy-to-ab"
literal "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m_{AB}=-2.5log_{10}(DN\times10^{-9})\label{eq:sdsstomag}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
PS1 - for the convertion from PS1 data units to magnitudes we use the zero
 point, which is the magnitude of an object with a count rate of 1.
 PS1's zero point is normalized and equals 25 for all the fits files, so
 the convertion from data units to magnitudes is the following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ps1-units-to-mag"
literal "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m_{AB}=-2.5log_{10}DN+25+2.5log_{10}(t_{exp})\label{eq:mag_ps1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{exp}$
\end_inset

 is the exposure time for a stack in seconds, and it is given in the fits
 file header under 'EXPTIME'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Celestial-units to Pixels
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a fits file and an object's celectial coordinates, we want to be able
 to convert distances from sky units (arcsec) to pixels in the fits image,
 so if we choose an aperture radius in arc seconds, we can find the aperture
 radius in pixels.
 The details of this convertion vary between the two survey data products:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
PS1 - the convertion is the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
arcsec=\frac{1}{3600\cdot CDELT1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Where CDELT1 is the ratio of degrees to pixel in each fits file, and it
 can be found in the header under 'CDELT1'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
SDSS - the convertion is the following: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
arcsec=\frac{1}{\sqrt{(CD1\_2\cdot3600)^{2}+(CD2\_2\cdot3600)^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Where 
\color black
CD1_2 and CD2_2
\color inherit
 are RA and DEC degrees per row pixel, and they can be found in the header
 under 'CD1_2' and 'CD2_2'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Later we can use this covertion to convert the aperture radius to calculate
 the background, as described in the next section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important part of calculating photometry, is subtructing the image's
 background from the source counts, since the sky and unresolved emission
 can create background light, and there might be another light emitter close
 to the object (or in front of it) that can add light to the DN.
 To calculate the background we set 3 radii: small, medium and large, such
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $radii=[r,2r,3r]$
\end_inset

, where r is the aperture radius used for the source measurment.
 The background is calculated in the ring between medium and large radii
 (the big ring), since between the small and the medium radii some light
 from the object might be present.
 To sum pixels within a circular aperture, where (x,y) is the location of
 the object in pixels, the pixels that are added to the sum are the ones
 within [x-3r, x+3r] and [y-3r, y+3r] and also where their distance from
 (x,y) is in the range [2r, 3r].
 Here we denote DN as the set of count values that are within the big ring.
 The background is calculated using:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
bg=median(x_{bg})
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{bg}$
\end_inset

 is the set of count values in the big ring.
 The background uncertainty is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta bg=\frac{SDT(x_{bg})}{\sqrt{n}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where n is the number of pixels in the big ring.
 In the calculation of the uncertainty I neglect the poisson distribution
 uncertainty, since the statistical uncertainty (as we saw in our measurments)
 is the dominent one.
 Equations 5 and 6 give as the median and the uncertainty of the background
 in one pixel, so to calculate the background subtracted source counts:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
DN_{cor}=DN-bg\cdot\pi r^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

To find the total background uncertainty we multiply the uncertainty by
 the circle area:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta bg_{tot}=bg_{err}\cdot\pi r^{2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
uncertainties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important factor we need to address here is the gain: in CCD imaging,
 gain refers to the amplification a given system will produce 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gain"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The DN is calculated using:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
DN=\frac{electrons}{gain}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where electrons is the number of electrons that encountered the measuring
 instrument.
 We can find the gain of every image in the fits file header: in PS1 it's
 under 'HIERARCH CELL.GAIN' and in SDSS it's under 'NMGY' (NMGY is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{gain}$
\end_inset

 so for SDSS 
\begin_inset Formula $DN=NMGY\cdot electrons$
\end_inset

).
 The gain is important when calculating the uncertainties, since we know
 that the electron counts follow a poisson distribution, but we need to
 find the uncertainties for DN.
 The DN's inaccuracy consists of 2 quantities: the poisson distribution
 uncertainty of the electron count and the uncertainty in background determinati
on.
 The poisson distribution uncertainty we calculate with:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta pois=\frac{1}{gain}\sqrt{DN\cdot gain}=\sqrt{\frac{DN}{gain}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

And the background inaccuracy is calculated in equation 8.
 We therefore find the total inaccuracy:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta DN=\sqrt{\Delta pois^{2}+\Delta bg_{tot}^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The final step in calculating the uncertainties is converting them to magnitudes.
 Due to the logarithmic nature of the DN-to-mag convertion, the uncertainties
 are not symmetric, so we get 2 different uncertainties when converting
 to magnitude: up and down.
 We denote 
\begin_inset Formula $Mag(val)$
\end_inset

 as the convertion of val to magnitudes, using eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sdsstomag"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mag_ps1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The uncertainties are calculated with:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{-}=|Mag(DN_{cor}+\Delta DN)-Mag(DN_{cor})|
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta_{+}=|Mag(DN_{cor}-\Delta DN)-Mag(DN_{cor})
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{-}$
\end_inset

 is the down inaccuracy and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{+}$
\end_inset

 is the up inaccuracy, both in magnitudes.
 The uncertainty range is 
\begin_inset Formula $[DN_{cor}-\Delta_{-},DN_{cor}+\Delta_{+}]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
concederations in choosing Aperture Radius
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To choose the aperture radius correctly we need to understand PSF.
 The PSF - point spread function - of an optical device is the image of
 a single point object (see figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:psf"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 the PSF is an atrribute of the optical instrument used to capture images,
 so the degree of spreading (blurring) in the image of this point object
 is a measure for the quality of an optical system.
 The PSF causes the point object to spread to an elliptical shape, but the
 sum of light from the object is conserved (though we need to change the
 aperture to capture all of it).
 To try and capture the light from the spread object, we can use the PSF's
 FWHM (full-width-half-maximum) as the aperture radius.
 Since the object is elliptical, we have 2 FWHMs - major axis and minor
 axis - we will use their average as the aperture radius.
 In a 2-D gaussian, 
\begin_inset Formula $FWHM\thickapprox2.355\sigma$
\end_inset

, so the percentage of area under the gaussian that is bounded by the FWHM
 is about 93.75% (when assuming the PSF is a 2D circular gaussian) .
 Therefore, to find the sum of the light count within 1 PSF, we can use
 the FWHM as the aperture radius, and then divide the result by 0.9375.
\end_layout

